>>179518348
>I love TOS but it isn't even close to the quality of writing that Voyager is
Voyager was too unoriginal - almost every episode was derivitive of some older Trek episode, be it a TOS or a TNG or even a DS9 episode. It was a redundant and pointless show, because it didn't commit to its few actually new and interesting ideas. Also, nobody on the cast had a fraction of the charisma or natural likeability of the Kirk-Spock-Bones trio, except the Doctor.
TOS, as dated and cheesy as a lot it is now, was revolutionary and groundbreaking at the time, and filled to the brim with exciting new ideas and concepts. Voyager came after we'd already had ~over 200 Trek episodes in eight years, and there simply wasn't much left for it to do. So much of it felt like it was just going through the motions.

>>179528198
To give you a filmfag answer, film has virtually infinite "resolution", down to individual silver halide crystals in the emulsion (it gets a little more complicated for color film, which is obviously majority, but I'm simplifying - but technically, B&W film literally has only two colors, black and white, and we perceive it as infinite scale of grey because of their density at microscopic resolution). The characteristics of the grain are important too and make part of the image, remember the seething about DNR (digital nose reduction) and many releases killed by it, like Predator or T2. Then you have film speed, or sensitivity to light (colloquially your might have heard of ISO sensitivity in digital cameras), which is directly related and inversely proportional to the size of silver halide crystal "grains" (ie. larger grains > higher sensitivity > can shoot in lower light > but image is more grainy). But we're not watching movies under a microscope. And another factor is optical resolution of the camera lens, on top of whether focus puller did a good job to get the scene pin sharp. Finally you can't look at each part separately, it's all compounded and interacting, eg. slightly coarse grain makes slightly blurry image perceptibly sharper.
Anyway 4K is a good sweet spot for resolution for movies shot on 35mm stock. I've been scanning 35mm still photos on professional scanners for some 20 years now, usually at 4000 dpi which gives you about 5600x3800 pixel image, and there is hardly more you could squeeze out of them in 99.9% cases. And remember that motion picture frame is shot with film running vertically, so in that case (assuming 22x16mm Academy format) you would get about 3400x2900 pixels. The master transfer should be done at 8k resolution for editing overhead, but for release 4k is ideal, and the limiting factor is now bit depth and video compression and bandwidth.

>>179524798
Potions were broken in Morrowind. They made them infinitely stackable and thus infinitely scaleable. The only thing to delay you becoming a God was gathering ingredients which required a time/ money investment and so required a certain degree of levelling before the player could break the game. A poorly designed system that breaks the game isn’t good design, not because it isn’t (temporarily) fun, but because without challenge the entire gameplay loop of an RPG gets broken. There’s no point to levelling or acquiring loot when you’ve brewed a stack of potions that give you 37,000 strength for 68 minutes, and because there’s no point levelling or acquiring loot, there’s no point to doing any of the content. Dialogue and story aren’t reward enough - you need challenge for immersion otherwise the dissonance is complete. Playing the final boss battle with potion-hacked strength robs it of its drama and tension. It’s the equivalent of watching the finale of a Michael Bay movie where all the giant robots have been replaced by action figures being bashed together by a child.

>>179524243

In the first half they're all just people doing business, but the groundwork for the crew's whole dislike of Ash is laid. Ash's robotic, demoralizing contempt for humanity is also well done, and well directed by Ridley. To the last, this thing wants to demoralize them in order to carry out its task. It almost succeeds.

Ripley and Dallas get along okay. Dallas and Kane too. Parker and Brett are a unit. Parker gives Ripley and Lambert some shit, but it's not too far and they get along okay. Ash is the odd man out.

OTOH, I like to imagine that when Ash tells Ripley that there's a reasonable explanation, it meant it. One can imagine predators or space terminators or Na'vi or god knows what else about to descend on humanity, and certain suits have decided that having some weaponized aliens might not be a bad idea.

There's a scene which is ONLY present in the 1979 theatrical original (the better cut), and is ABSENT in the 2003 "directors's cut". This is right after Ash insists that they keep the dead facehugger aboard and Dallas consents. Ripley confronts him that this is bullshit, and Dallas explains that Ash was subbed in just before they shipped out this time. This is an extremely important story detail which explains the Ash character, and helps the (virginal) audience to build distrust for the character.

Ian Holm really did a great job as the cold robot villlain, and it's nice that he got later popular sci-fi/fantasy roles (Bilbo, the very human priest guy in Fifth Element), along with the Shakespeare and other stuff. RIP.

>>179525887

When you do a hyper-autistic (close read) on the differences between both versions, yes, it bears out. Standard DVD/Blu-ray releases tout the ADDED material going from 1979 to 2003, but they ELIDE AND IGNORE the DELETIONS. You have to do your own viewing and note-taking to check those. The detail about Ash getting subbed in at the last minute, which Dallas tells Ripley in the cramped hallway, is only present in the 1979 original. It's the worst story change, because that bit is the most important loss.

Also worse is the lost single shot of Brett's long, close-up single take for over 30 seconds, where he just mugs for the camera.

I also don't care for how the 2003 DC had Lambert SLAM Ripley once let back inside, although I admit it does make dramatic sense. I had an old friend who liked the addition. I still retain my ticket stub when some of us watched the new cut on Halloween, 2003.
